data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code uses only `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — none of these are affected by the .NET 6+ breaking change. They work identically on .NET 8. There are no calls to `Thread.Abort`, no `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks, and no `Thread.ResetAbort` or `Thread.Interrupt` usage.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort migration): you could replace the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll` for cleaner code:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken token = default)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, token, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        await Task.Delay(100, ct); // replaces Thread.Sleep
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

But again, this is purely optional — your existing code requires no changes for the .NET 8 migration.
